In this area you can see a few of the last remaining windmills. Once painted by the famous Van Gogh. Check it out if you are in the area.

Hidden away a bit we saw it in autumn so there wasn't much leaf coverage. We didn't appear to be able to get too close but you can a view around the back from the road too. Lovely old mill, there's a smaller one up the road too.

The Blute-fin has been standing since the Middle Ages, according to the history of the Debray family it was built in 1295. Unfortunately it is currently closed to the public. On the property there were two mills: the Blute-fin and the Radet.

Only the windmill structure is still original from the time Montmartre was not as developed as it is today, and everything else is relatively newly built. It's also the place where Renoir painted his famous and at the time controversial painting, "Bal du moulin de la Galette". It's an interesting place to look at while passing by.

It's not impressive or grand, but it's worth seeing. Apparently it is the last one of its kind in Paris and there is a legend about its owner. It's worth checking out this place, especially since it's located right on the main street of Montmartre.

I went there for a walk with the plan of showing a real mill to a 3 year old child (if you know of others in the Paris region I'm interested) From the square near the Moulin Rouge (especially don't come by the Pigalle metro with a child, only cheap shops), take the friendly Rue Lepic with lots of bakeries, rotisseries, etc. Then we climb even higher and we see the famous mill appear: the Blute Fin mill. It's really nice to look at, but private property so there's no question of going up to see it up close. There is a second mill right next door, 2 rue Girardon: Moulin Radet. Afterwards I went up a little further to settle down at the Suzanne Bushes square which can give the little ones a nice play break (sandbox, two slides) and numerous benches for picnics. Going down to see the wall of I love you with the rue d'orechamp I passed in front of the boat wash house.
Old wooden mill, I am surprised to see it all over Montmarte. It is a charming neighborhood, as if you were outside of Paris. That mill overlooks a restaurant.
